# LINUX LAB EXERCISE – BASIC FILE & DIRECTORY COMMANDS

# Exercise 1: Create Directories

## Create a Single Directory

mkdir <directory_name>

Task:

* Create a directory with any name of your choice.
* Verify using ls.

## Create Multiple Directories

mkdir <directory1> <directory2>

Task:

* Create two directories at the same time.

## Create Multiple Numbered Directories

mkdir <directory_prefix>{1..5}

Example:
project1
project2
project3
project4
project5

Task:

* Create 5 numbered directories using brace expansion.

# Exercise 2: Create Files

## Create a Single File

touch <file_name>

Task:

* Create one empty file.

## Create Multiple Files

touch <file1> <file2> <file3>

Task:

* Create three files in a single command.

## Create Multiple Numbered Files

touch <file_prefix>{1..5}

Task:

* Create five numbered files.

# Exercise 3: Write Data into Files

## Create a New File and Add Content

cat > <file_name>

Type some text and press:

Ctrl + D

Task:

* Create a file and add at least three lines of text.

## Append Data to an Existing File

cat >> <file_name>

Type additional text and press:

Ctrl + D

Task:

* Append at least two new lines to the file.

# Exercise 4: View File Contents

## Display Entire File

cat <file_name>

Task:

* View the contents of your file.

# Exercise 5: Remove Files and Directories

## Remove a File

rm <file_name>

Task:

* Delete a file.

## Remove an Empty Directory

rmdir <directory_name>

Task:

* Delete an empty directory.

## Force Remove a Directory

rm -rf <directory_name>

Task:

* Delete a directory and its contents without confirmation.

# Exercise 6: Navigation Commands

## Move into a Directory

cd <directory_name>

## Move into Nested Directories

cd <directory1>/<directory2>/<directory3>

## Return to Previous Directory

cd -

## Go to Home Directory

cd

## Display Present Working Directory

pwd

Task:

* Navigate between directories and record the output of pwd.

# Exercise 7: Listing Files and Directories

## Basic Listing

ls

## Detailed Listing

ls -l

## Show Hidden Files

ls -la

## Sort by Modification Time

ls -lt

# File Viewing Commands

## Display First 10 Lines

cat <file_name> | head

## Display First 2 Lines

cat <file_name> | head -2

## Display First 20 Lines

head -20 <file_name>

## Display Last 15 Lines

cat <file_name> | tail -15

## Display Last 10 Lines

tail <file_name>

## View File Using less

cat <file_name> | less

or

less <file_name>

## View File Using more

cat <file_name> | more

or

more <file_name>

# Searching Text using grep

## Search for a Keyword

cat <file_name> | grep <keyword_to_search>

# Exercise 11: Copy Files and Directories

## Copy a File

cp <source_file> <destination>

# Exercise 12: Move and Rename

## Move a File

mv <file_name> <destination_directory>

## Move a Directory

mv <directory_name> <destination_directory>

## Rename a File

mv <old_file_name> <new_file_name>

# Exercise 13: Miscellaneous Commands

## Write Text to a File

echo "<text>" > <file_name>

# Other Useful Commands

## Display Kernel Name

uname

## Display Complete System Information

uname -a

## Clear the Terminal Screen

clear

## Display Logged-in Users and Activities

w

## Display Logged-in Users

who

## Display Current Username

whoami
